00:00:09.140 --> 00:00:11.370
SRIDHAR RAMASWAMY:
Good afternoon.

00:00:11.370 --> 00:00:13.105
My name is Sridhar
Ramaswamy, I'm

00:00:13.105 --> 00:00:18.820
the SVP for ads and
payments at Google.

00:00:18.820 --> 00:00:22.520
As you saw in [? Sundar's ?]
keynote in the morning,

00:00:22.520 --> 00:00:26.910
the Android platform
has tremendous momentum.

00:00:26.910 --> 00:00:30.010
And today I'm very
pleased to tell you

00:00:30.010 --> 00:00:32.380
about the next
generation of payments

00:00:32.380 --> 00:00:36.377
that we are going to
be doing on Android.

00:00:36.377 --> 00:00:37.960
Of course, it's 3:00
in the afternoon,

00:00:37.960 --> 00:00:39.975
and we wanted to perk you
guys up to start with,

00:00:39.975 --> 00:00:43.090
so we thought we would start
by showing a funny picture

00:00:43.090 --> 00:00:46.322
of cute babies or cute cats.

00:00:46.322 --> 00:00:50.190
We did a lot of research
and went with cute babies.

00:00:52.860 --> 00:00:55.860
But we realized we could
also use this picture

00:00:55.860 --> 00:00:58.810
to make a really
important point, which

00:00:58.810 --> 00:01:05.060
is last year four times as
many Android devices were sold

00:01:05.060 --> 00:01:08.841
every day as were babies born.

00:01:08.841 --> 00:01:10.340
Our activation
numbers are something

00:01:10.340 --> 00:01:13.980
like a million and a
half devices activated

00:01:13.980 --> 00:01:17.010
every single day.

00:01:17.010 --> 00:01:20.660
That's, like, some babies
with a lot of phones.

00:01:20.660 --> 00:01:24.390
And what's also amazing
about the rise of smartphones

00:01:24.390 --> 00:01:29.950
in general is the
tremendous engagement

00:01:29.950 --> 00:01:33.820
that consumers have
with these devices.

00:01:33.820 --> 00:01:40.800
The average consumer takes their
phones out 150 times a day.

00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:45.950
That's close to 10
for every waking hour.

00:01:45.950 --> 00:01:50.550
And these devices, which
not so long ago were just

00:01:50.550 --> 00:01:52.930
simple things for
making phone calls,

00:01:52.930 --> 00:01:57.010
have almost become
extensions of ourselves.

00:01:57.010 --> 00:02:00.120
Close to 2/3 of us
sleep with our phones

00:02:00.120 --> 00:02:01.190
right next to our bed.

00:02:01.190 --> 00:02:02.940
It's the first thing
I touch every morning

00:02:02.940 --> 00:02:04.320
to turn off my alarm.

00:02:04.320 --> 00:02:07.360
And through the day we use our
phones for texting our loved

00:02:07.360 --> 00:02:09.740
ones, looking up directions,
checking up on traffic,

00:02:09.740 --> 00:02:12.820
seeing what the weather's like,
being amused and entertained,

00:02:12.820 --> 00:02:16.622
buying stuff online,
the list goes on and on.

00:02:16.622 --> 00:02:19.640
And in fact, we are all more
likely to check to make sure

00:02:19.640 --> 00:02:22.090
that we have our
phones in our pockets

00:02:22.090 --> 00:02:24.400
when we leave our home
than we are to check

00:02:24.400 --> 00:02:28.920
for our wallet or our keys.

00:02:28.920 --> 00:02:31.360
That's pretty amazing.

00:02:31.360 --> 00:02:37.340
But there is one thing that
we do not yet commonly do

00:02:37.340 --> 00:02:42.010
as consumers, and that is
pay for physical purchases

00:02:42.010 --> 00:02:42.779
with our phones.

00:02:46.611 --> 00:02:51.690
Four years ago, we
pioneered a technology

00:02:51.690 --> 00:02:54.540
to store payment
credentials securely

00:02:54.540 --> 00:02:58.550
on the phone using a
technology called Near Field

00:02:58.550 --> 00:03:00.980
Communication, or NFC.

00:03:00.980 --> 00:03:04.620
We also pioneered a scheme by
which these credentials could

00:03:04.620 --> 00:03:10.670
be securely transmitted to
merchant point of sale devices

00:03:10.670 --> 00:03:11.670
to complete the payment.

00:03:11.670 --> 00:03:13.070
We called the
scheme tap and pay.

00:03:16.510 --> 00:03:19.840
And we are excited
today because we

00:03:19.840 --> 00:03:24.820
think the overall
ecosystem is at a point

00:03:24.820 --> 00:03:28.370
that these payments can
achieve massive scale.

00:03:31.200 --> 00:03:32.130
Why do we say that?

00:03:32.130 --> 00:03:37.420
We think the current world is
ready, both at a consumer level

00:03:37.420 --> 00:03:40.340
and at a merchant level,
and these are two really,

00:03:40.340 --> 00:03:43.590
really important prerequisites
for any large scale

00:03:43.590 --> 00:03:48.150
change to happen in a
complicated and important world

00:03:48.150 --> 00:03:49.920
like payments.

00:03:49.920 --> 00:03:53.530
To start with, on
the consumer side,

00:03:53.530 --> 00:03:58.320
seven out of ten Android
devices in use today

00:03:58.320 --> 00:04:01.125
are already capable of
making NFC payments.

00:04:03.650 --> 00:04:05.400
These are phones that
are out there today,

00:04:05.400 --> 00:04:08.610
being used by people.

00:04:08.610 --> 00:04:12.600
And pretty much every
new Android device

00:04:12.600 --> 00:04:20.260
that ships is also
capable of NFC payments.

00:04:20.260 --> 00:04:23.340
And this means
that consumers can

00:04:23.340 --> 00:04:27.160
go buy new Android phones
knowing that mobile payments

00:04:27.160 --> 00:04:28.860
just is there.

00:04:28.860 --> 00:04:31.850
They come along for the ride.

00:04:31.850 --> 00:04:35.070
And then on the
merchant side, there

00:04:35.070 --> 00:04:38.120
are over 700,000
merchant locations

00:04:38.120 --> 00:04:42.610
that can accept tap
and pay payments.

00:04:42.610 --> 00:04:47.040
And in fact, here's an amazing
little map of all the locations

00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:51.790
where people are using Android
phones to tap and pay today.

00:04:55.640 --> 00:04:59.050
And further, the merchant
ecosystem in the US

00:04:59.050 --> 00:05:02.740
is in the midst of an
upgrade cycle with respect

00:05:02.740 --> 00:05:06.190
to all of their point
of sale devices.

00:05:06.190 --> 00:05:09.100
That is going to provide
better security for all of us

00:05:09.100 --> 00:05:13.370
as consumers, but
also these devices

00:05:13.370 --> 00:05:18.740
will be capable of
accepting NFC payments.

00:05:18.740 --> 00:05:25.590
We really think that it is the
confluence of a huge number

00:05:25.590 --> 00:05:27.630
of devices-- consumer
devices-- in use,

00:05:27.630 --> 00:05:31.450
new ones that are coming out
being capable of making NFC

00:05:31.450 --> 00:05:33.480
payments, and the
fact that there

00:05:33.480 --> 00:05:38.080
is going to be a tremendous
upsurge in the number

00:05:38.080 --> 00:05:41.190
of merchant terminals that
can accept NFC payments that

00:05:41.190 --> 00:05:45.625
makes this a right moment
for big changes to happen.

00:05:48.670 --> 00:05:53.930
So we've been working to
create support for payments

00:05:53.930 --> 00:05:58.000
at a core platform
level in Android.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:03.430
And as you heard earlier,
we call this Android Pay.

00:06:07.200 --> 00:06:12.550
So Android Pay will be built
deep within the Android

00:06:12.550 --> 00:06:16.510
ecosystem, and it
is going to serve

00:06:16.510 --> 00:06:22.090
as the glue between
consumers and merchants.

00:06:22.090 --> 00:06:25.990
And we had a few core principles
that we adopted for Android

00:06:25.990 --> 00:06:29.565
Pay, and those were simplicity.

00:06:29.565 --> 00:06:33.700
It should be really easy
for all consumers to use.

00:06:33.700 --> 00:06:36.200
It should be secure.

00:06:36.200 --> 00:06:37.900
There's a lot of doubt
and worry that we

00:06:37.900 --> 00:06:40.250
have about the constant
stream of breaking news

00:06:40.250 --> 00:06:42.740
that we all keep hearing.

00:06:42.740 --> 00:06:47.400
And there should be
choice for consumers,

00:06:47.400 --> 00:06:50.070
in terms of the devices that
they use, in terms of the apps

00:06:50.070 --> 00:06:53.440
that they could use in order
to make these payments.

00:06:53.440 --> 00:06:56.630
And Android Pay is
going to be the solution

00:06:56.630 --> 00:07:03.100
both for physical payments at
stores but also for payments

00:07:03.100 --> 00:07:09.480
within the apps that we all
have on our Android phones.

00:07:09.480 --> 00:07:13.920
So it's going to solve the
problem of mobile payments

00:07:13.920 --> 00:07:16.710
in a pretty comprehensive way.

00:07:16.710 --> 00:07:19.250
I'm very pleased to
welcome Ariel Bardin, who

00:07:19.250 --> 00:07:22.630
is the Product Vice President
for Payments at Google,

00:07:22.630 --> 00:07:25.810
and Pali Bhat, the Director of
Consumer Payments at Google,

00:07:25.810 --> 00:07:28.510
to tell us a lot more
about Android Pay.

