00:07:54.613 --> 00:07:56.610
All right, back to business.

00:07:56.610 --> 00:07:58.910
So Sridhar talked about
a few core principles

00:07:58.910 --> 00:08:00.600
that we had when
we designed Android

00:08:00.600 --> 00:08:04.550
Pay along with our many
partners in the ecosystem.

00:08:04.550 --> 00:08:08.020
The first is simplicity,
second is security, and choice.

00:08:08.020 --> 00:08:09.470
So let's talk through all these.

00:08:09.470 --> 00:08:13.570
And let's focus specifically
on the real world, tap and pay,

00:08:13.570 --> 00:08:17.640
and we'll talk
next about in-app.

00:08:17.640 --> 00:08:20.190
Simplicity.

00:08:20.190 --> 00:08:22.730
We want to unlock our
phone, tap, and be done,

00:08:22.730 --> 00:08:25.220
and that should be
a very easy process.

00:08:25.220 --> 00:08:28.870
And of course, credit cards
and debit cards need to work.

00:08:28.870 --> 00:08:33.210
We need to be able to use them
very easily on our phones.

00:08:33.210 --> 00:08:35.110
But we didn't want
to stop there.

00:08:35.110 --> 00:08:40.000
When you talk to users, they
do other things at the store

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:42.380
when they actually check out.

00:08:42.380 --> 00:08:47.650
Some will use a gift card,
some will use a loyalty card,

00:08:47.650 --> 00:08:50.550
and some will use coupons.

00:08:50.550 --> 00:08:52.560
So we want to take all
of this information

00:08:52.560 --> 00:08:55.210
and pass it during
the tap, make it very,

00:08:55.210 --> 00:08:57.760
very simple for users to use it.

00:08:57.760 --> 00:09:00.250
We'll start with loyalty.

00:09:00.250 --> 00:09:04.230
And Pali will show us a really
cool demo with that machine

00:09:04.230 --> 00:09:08.440
that I'm assuming you're
wondering why it's here.

00:09:08.440 --> 00:09:09.860
He'll show us how
we can integrate

00:09:09.860 --> 00:09:12.960
both a payment and
loyalty information right

00:09:12.960 --> 00:09:18.150
within one tap and make it very,
very easy and simple to use.

00:09:18.150 --> 00:09:20.060
Let's talk about security.

00:09:20.060 --> 00:09:24.600
As Sridhar said, nobody wants
to have problems with their card

00:09:24.600 --> 00:09:29.870
number after a purchase
and worry about it.

00:09:29.870 --> 00:09:34.290
So we partnered with
the financial networks,

00:09:34.290 --> 00:09:39.890
the payments networks,
to adopt tokenization

00:09:39.890 --> 00:09:42.830
so that we don't have to
store the actual credit card

00:09:42.830 --> 00:09:44.650
information on the
phone, and I'll

00:09:44.650 --> 00:09:47.100
talk about that a
little bit in a moment.

00:09:47.100 --> 00:09:49.520
The second thing
we do is we look

00:09:49.520 --> 00:09:53.260
at over 100 signals
with our own risk engine

00:09:53.260 --> 00:09:55.510
before we let a
transaction go through

00:09:55.510 --> 00:09:58.000
and when a card is
added to the phone.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:00.317
So we've got a
software solution,

00:10:00.317 --> 00:10:02.400
but we don't stop there,
we also look at hardware.

00:10:02.400 --> 00:10:05.760
And as you heard in
the keynote, starting

00:10:05.760 --> 00:10:08.910
with the M release
of Android we will

00:10:08.910 --> 00:10:10.810
support fingerprint
authentication

00:10:10.810 --> 00:10:13.360
as well to really bring the
hardware and the software

00:10:13.360 --> 00:10:16.300
together and provide a
great level of security

00:10:16.300 --> 00:10:17.030
for our users.

00:10:19.640 --> 00:10:23.296
So the third key principle
that Sridhar talked about that

00:10:23.296 --> 00:10:24.920
was kind of core to
the way we designed

00:10:24.920 --> 00:10:29.090
Android Pay was choice.

00:10:29.090 --> 00:10:31.510
In Android, we have a
principal of openness.

00:10:31.510 --> 00:10:35.120
We love a lot of innovation.

00:10:35.120 --> 00:10:36.035
It's that exciting?

00:10:38.540 --> 00:10:40.620
Your phone jumped
out of your lap.

00:10:40.620 --> 00:10:44.555
Make sure the credit
card is in it, please.

00:10:44.555 --> 00:10:45.180
So where was I?

00:10:45.180 --> 00:10:46.090
Yes.

00:10:46.090 --> 00:10:47.080
So we like innovation.

00:10:47.080 --> 00:10:48.452
We want to have open systems.

00:10:48.452 --> 00:10:50.410
Having open systems drives
a lot of innovation,

00:10:50.410 --> 00:10:51.300
it's good for users.

00:10:51.300 --> 00:10:53.095
Users like choice.

00:10:53.095 --> 00:10:54.595
So when you think
about tap and pay,

00:10:54.595 --> 00:10:56.510
there has to be hardware
that actually supports it,

00:10:56.510 --> 00:10:58.950
and almost all phones today--
all Android phones today--

00:10:58.950 --> 00:11:03.560
have the hardware needed
to actually do a tap.

00:11:03.560 --> 00:11:08.650
In 2012, we added a layer on
top of that as part of KitKat

00:11:08.650 --> 00:11:10.779
called host card emulation.

00:11:10.779 --> 00:11:12.820
What host card emulation
did was allow developers

00:11:12.820 --> 00:11:15.730
to access that hardware so
that they could build apps

00:11:15.730 --> 00:11:19.590
on top of tap and pay,
or they could also

00:11:19.590 --> 00:11:21.850
use the hardware
for other use cases,

00:11:21.850 --> 00:11:24.494
like opening doors, et cetera.

00:11:24.494 --> 00:11:25.910
What we're doing
with Android Pay,

00:11:25.910 --> 00:11:30.950
though, is we're introducing
a new layer, an API, which

00:11:30.950 --> 00:11:35.650
will allow developers-- approved
developers-- to get access

00:11:35.650 --> 00:11:38.980
to the same tokenization
services that we use to power

00:11:38.980 --> 00:11:39.760
tap and pay.

00:11:39.760 --> 00:11:44.990
So think of this as a new
layer on top of the raw iron.

00:11:44.990 --> 00:11:48.480
What this means for users is
that they can use the Android

00:11:48.480 --> 00:11:52.200
Pay app to make payments--
set up their cards,

00:11:52.200 --> 00:11:53.710
pick which card
they want to use,

00:11:53.710 --> 00:11:55.930
all that good
stuff-- or they can

00:11:55.930 --> 00:12:02.720
use one of approved partner
apps, bank apps, et cetera.

00:12:02.720 --> 00:12:04.585
And Pali will be
showing a demo of how

00:12:04.585 --> 00:12:05.835
that'll work in a few minutes.

00:12:10.590 --> 00:12:12.770
Now, that's a lot to do.

00:12:12.770 --> 00:12:14.360
It's not easy.

00:12:14.360 --> 00:12:16.710
And the famous saying
is, it takes a village,

00:12:16.710 --> 00:12:20.660
and it certainly takes
a village in this case.

00:12:20.660 --> 00:12:23.570
So let's talk
about all the folks

00:12:23.570 --> 00:12:27.010
that we're working with
across the payments ecosystem

00:12:27.010 --> 00:12:29.240
that Sridhar referenced before.

00:12:29.240 --> 00:12:31.650
So first, we're
working with carriers

00:12:31.650 --> 00:12:35.460
to make sure that all users
can get access to Android Pay

00:12:35.460 --> 00:12:37.470
easily.

00:12:37.470 --> 00:12:41.750
We're working with AT&amp;T,
Verizon, and T-Mobile,

00:12:41.750 --> 00:12:44.210
so that when you buy
a new Android phone,

00:12:44.210 --> 00:12:48.320
it'll come preloaded
with Android Pay.

00:12:48.320 --> 00:12:49.810
But we don't stop there.

00:12:49.810 --> 00:12:51.510
When you walk into
the store, you

00:12:51.510 --> 00:12:54.940
should walk out with Android
Pay set up, ready to go.

00:12:54.940 --> 00:12:57.070
So the sales people
in the stores

00:12:57.070 --> 00:12:58.840
will be able to
help users set up

00:12:58.840 --> 00:13:01.750
their phones with
Android Pay, add

00:13:01.750 --> 00:13:04.740
the relevant cards, et cetera.

00:13:04.740 --> 00:13:07.630
Now, Android Pay will work
on any carrier's phone that

00:13:07.630 --> 00:13:11.630
has KitKat, and there's tens
of millions of these phones,

00:13:11.630 --> 00:13:16.290
and more and more every day, as
the babies illustrated earlier.

00:13:19.740 --> 00:13:25.480
The second folks we partnered
with are the payment networks.

00:13:25.480 --> 00:13:29.740
And the payment networks
helped us with tokenization,

00:13:29.740 --> 00:13:31.870
that I mentioned before,
and what tokenization

00:13:31.870 --> 00:13:36.780
allows us to do is not store
your credit card number

00:13:36.780 --> 00:13:39.300
on the phone, but rather
give it to the networks

00:13:39.300 --> 00:13:44.270
and get back a virtual account
number that we can securely

00:13:44.270 --> 00:13:46.260
store on the phone.

00:13:46.260 --> 00:13:47.935
So that's a critical
part of Android Pay

00:13:47.935 --> 00:13:50.387
and how it works, and
this partnership is

00:13:50.387 --> 00:13:51.470
extremely important to us.

00:13:55.890 --> 00:14:00.360
We're also working with the
leading financial institutions,

00:14:00.360 --> 00:14:03.770
so you can securely use your
existing debit and credit

00:14:03.770 --> 00:14:07.170
cards along with Android Pay.

00:14:09.509 --> 00:14:11.300
And actually, before
I go to the merchants,

00:14:11.300 --> 00:14:13.360
we have a bunch of
these folks in the room,

00:14:13.360 --> 00:14:18.070
and I have a note that
